Aaaaanyhow, other then putting AD and the others on rotations, what could the RTA really do to effect this?<br>
<br>
The RTA has the power to enforce its rules because the gains from working within the system vastly outweight the loss from getting kicked out of the system, so everyone generally plays along nicely.  Does the RTA currently address anything beyond planer reservations and rotations arrangements?  Like general conventions on non-rotation mobs?  If so, how are those rules decided?<br>
<br>
And related to that, who has the &quot;right&quot; to make rules about non-rotation mobs?  A vote by all guild reps maybe?<br>
<br>
What might be the penalties for breaking these non-rotation agreements?<br>
<br>
I am concerned that the RTA might overstep its current &quot;authority&quot; if it makes some sort of rule about non-rotation flagging mobs.  I worry about rules that some guilds might be tempted to ignore because they do not think the rule is valid.  (Not saying that my guild would ignore them, or that I would ignore them, but obviously some people in this thread feel very strongly about the issue.)  I think a good comparision might be someone who breaks a law that they think is unconstitutional.<br>
